06740nam a22013095i 9780691228365DE-B159720221107062033.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221107t20211988nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2020759494  a9780691228365  a(DE-B1597)576622  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aB67 7aPHI0040002bisacsh04a1211 aMiller, Richard W., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFact and Method :bExplanation, Confirmation and Reality in the Natural and the Social Sciences /cRichard W. Miller. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2021] 4c©1988  a1 online resource (628 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION. Replacing Positivism -- tPART ONE: Explanation -- tCHAPTER ONE. Explanation: The Covering-Law Model -- tCHAPTER TWO. The Nature of Explanation -- tCHAPTER THREE. Applications -- tPART TWO: Confirmation -- tCHAPTER FOUR. Confirmation as Causal Comparison -- tCHAPTER FIVE. Deductivism: Plain and with Simplicity -- tCHAPTER SIX. The New Positivism -- tCHAPTER SEVEN. Anti-Bayes -- tPART THREE: Realism -- tCHAPTER EIGHT. The Issue of Realism -- tCHAPTER NINE. Learning from Anti-Realism -- tCHAPTER TEN. A Defense of Realism -- tCHAPTER ELEVEN. Quantum Reality -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this bold work, of broad scope and rich erudition, Richard Miller sets out to reorient the philosophy of science. By questioning both positivism and its leading critics, he develops new solutions to the most urgent problems about justification, explanation, and truth. Using a wealth of examples from both the natural and the social sciences, Fact and Method applies the new account of scientific reason to specific questions of method in virtually every field of inquiry, including biology, physics, history, sociology, anthropology, economics, psychology, and literary theory. Explicit and up-to-date analysis of leading alternative views and a wealth of examples make it an ideal introduction to the philosophy of science, as well as a powerful attempt to change the field. Like the works of Hempel, Reichenbach, and Nagel in an earlier generation, it will challenge, instruct, and help anyone with an interest in science and its limits.For the past quarter-century, the philosophy of science has been in a crisis brought on by the failure of the positivist project of resolving all basic methodological questions by applying absolutely general rules, valid for all fields at all times. Professor Miller presents a new view in which what counts as an explanation, a cause, a confirming test, or a compelling case for the existence of an unobservable is determined by frameworks of specific substantive principles, rationally adopted in the light of the actual history of inquiry. While the history of science has usually been the material for relativism, Professor Miller uses arguments of Darwin, Newton, Einstein, Galileo, and others both to undermine positivist conceptions of rationality and to support the positivists' optimism that important theoretical findings are often justifiable from all reasonable perspectives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aCausation. 0aPositivism. 0aRealism. 0aSciencexPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Epistemology.2bisacsh  aAristotelian science.  aBayesianism.  aBayes’ Theorem.  aBernoulli process.  aBertrand’s paradox.  aBoyle-Charles law.  aCopenhagen interpretation.  aHamiltonian operator.  aKing Lear.  aMarxist social theory.  aNazi seizure of power.  aacceptance.  aanomalies.  aantirealism.  aapproximate truth.  aatomic theory.  acaloric.  acat paradox.  acausal checklists.  achemistry.  